The paper proposes a novel approach to event extraction using machine-readable natural language sentences based on annotation guidelines. This falls under the domain of natural language processing (NLP) and specifically, information extraction. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). Additionally, the paper introduces a model that incrementally replaces the bleached arguments in a statement with responses obtained by querying text with the statement itself, which involves machine learning and artificial intelligence techniques, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) another likely sub-category. The model also involves generalization to unseen event types, which could involve techniques from machine learning and statistical modeling, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) another possible sub-category. The paper also involves querying text, which could involve information retrieval techniques, making cs.IR (Information Retrieval) another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the extraction of events, which could involve techniques from neural networks and deep learning, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) another possible sub-category.
